00:28.440 --> 00:33.900
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.560 --> 00:38.320
And here are your hosts.

00:43.060 --> 00:50.880
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Norman Spinrad has strong opinions about
science fiction and its place in today's world. As a noted author who helped

00:50.880 --> 00:58.740
bring the science fiction new wave to this country, and as two-time president of
the Science Fiction Writers of America, Spinrad's ideas should be heard. One

00:58.740 --> 01:07.700
thing he feels strongly about is that science fiction has not been treated
fairly by book reviewers. As a category, you know, it is treated very unfairly

01:07.700 --> 01:19.540
and very cavalierly by the powers that be, which is mainly the New York Times
Book Review and the New York Review of Books and the so-called New York Literary

01:19.540 --> 01:27.740
Establishment, which really does have a very heavy effect on the way books are
published. These people, for instance, came down on the American Book Awards,

01:27.920 --> 01:36.820
succeeded in getting science fiction knocked out of the American Book Awards. A
real small clique of people in New York City who felt that it was really bad to

01:36.820 --> 01:44.520
have these awards given to things like science fiction, that it was bad to take
it away from a small jury which they could control and have thousands of people

01:44.520 --> 01:55.080
voting for. A very elitist, social fascist bunch of people who I have absolutely
no use for. And I'm sure they have no use for me. As president of the Science

01:55.080 --> 02:03.500
Fiction Writers of America, Spinrad has worked for some changes in the field.
One thing that I'm already halfway through getting done is to internationalize

02:03.500 --> 02:10.700
it, is to have an overseas region with an overseas director on our board of
directors. Because science fiction writing and publishing really is an

02:10.700 --> 02:19.300
international community. American writers sell their work all over the world.
English writers sell their work here. Foreign language writers have different

02:19.300 --> 02:26.380
problems. And we're all dealing with the same publishers. It certainly is an
international literature. And it's a spirit of the future and the spirit of

02:26.380 --> 02:34.440
internationalism and so forth. I felt it should be an international
organization. That's one thing. The other thing that I want to do and halfway to

02:34.440 --> 02:41.980
doing is upgrading the Nebula Awards. We have moved it out of the Warwick Hotel.
We're moving it into a much bigger room in the world often trying to make it

02:41.980 --> 02:52.060
into a more significant event than it has been. Again, orienting it towards the
world at large rather than towards the little in-group. Spinrad has always been

02:52.060 --> 02:58.300
concerned with the image science fiction has with the general public. He thinks
general readers should be made more aware of science fiction's unique

02:58.300 --> 03:07.280
possibilities and its genuine value. We asked him if science fiction movies have
a positive or negative influence on the public's image of the field. Oh, I don't

03:07.280 --> 03:17.620
know. I don't think they... Not really. I mean, the image of science fiction in
that respect has been very bad anyway. I don't think the movies really add to

03:17.620 --> 03:24.980
the image. But I don't think they detract from it either. If there were some
better, more sophisticated movies, they might help. Well, as it is, it's just

03:24.980 --> 03:33.840
kind of neutral publicity, people more aware that it exists. I think it's
positive, and it will prove to be positive in the long range, because a lot of

03:33.840 --> 03:41.200
people are being introduced to the imagery of science fiction, with which they
were unfamiliar through these movies. And if you look at the evolution in the

03:41.200 --> 03:48.420
movies, you find that in the earlier science fiction movies, if you're going
into space or whatever it is, you have to spend like half an hour setting the

03:48.420 --> 03:55.940
thing. This is a spaceship. It takes off from the Earth. People float around it.
You know, and you have to familiarize the audience with all this unfamiliar

03:55.940 --> 04:04.600
imagery. Now they can just start a movie, bang, right off, in a galaxy far away.
Boom. Here's a spaceship in the Stromo. Pow. You know, in other words, the first

04:04.600 --> 04:12.280
half hour of the conventional old-time science fiction movie is gone, because
people are now familiar with this imagery. And I think these movies have brought

04:12.280 --> 04:22.740
a lot of new people into familiarity with these images. They've made these
images part of the popular culture. These movies have been mainly aimed at kids

04:22.740 --> 04:34.480
and adolescents. And years from now, assuming that these people ever read
anything, they'll be ready to read science fiction of a more serious kind,

04:34.700 --> 04:41.780
assuming they're ready to read literature of a more serious kind at all, because
they'll be familiar with the material, familiar with the literature. It won't

04:41.780 --> 04:51.000
seem strange and weird to them because they will have grown up with it. That's
why I think magazines, even magazines like Starlogs, in that sense, will have a

04:51.000 --> 04:55.920
long-term positive impact. More with Norman Spinrad on our next show.

