06:25.840 --> 06:27.560
And here are your hosts.

06:32.520 --> 06:41.660
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Norman Spinrad's best-known novel may be Bug
Jack Barron, a book which has stirred controversy in both England and America. It

06:41.660 --> 06:49.460
was published in this country in 1969, and it's a different sort of science
fiction novel. It's a good example of new-wave science fiction. Character and

06:49.460 --> 06:57.520
style are important, and it deals with social issues such as racism, the
establishment, drugs, the power of the media, and radical protests. There is

06:57.520 --> 07:04.460
also a good deal of sex and violence in the book, and the language is highly
colored. But Spinrad thinks the plot of the book conforms to traditional science

07:04.460 --> 07:14.480
fiction formulas. Actually, what I was trying to do in a way, the book has a
very traditional plot. As far as I was concerned, it has a positive hero, it has

07:14.480 --> 07:23.680
a negative villain. The hero wins, the villain loses. All that stuff that is
considered, you know, the traditional way of plotting a book, and yet it's

07:23.680 --> 07:33.920
written in a different kind of way. It kind of takes that superficial kind of
plot and treats it in a realistic manner. The protagonist, Jack Barron, is a

07:33.920 --> 07:41.480
powerfully influential television star who has a talk show watched by 100
million people. He uses the show as a battlefield to oppose corrupt elements of

07:41.480 --> 07:49.260
society. Spinrad comments on Barron's use of power. The book is about power.

07:50.300 --> 08:01.200
Power itself is neutral as far as I'm concerned. It's what people do with it
that counts. Barron is a guy who likes power and keeps referring to it as a drug

08:02.120 --> 08:12.560
and knows that he can become addicted to it and for that reason has decided to
stay away from it. Then he gets drawn back into playing with power because he

08:12.560 --> 08:20.800
comes to the conclusion that it's better for somebody who feels that way about
power to be wielding it than people who don't have any self-consciousness about

08:20.800 --> 08:31.620
the dangers of wielding power. So in that sense, it's a comment on the power of
the media, but it's also a comment on the morality of power, on the paradox of

08:31.620 --> 08:43.480
power, which is that if you leave power to be wielded by people who do not see
the dangers, the personal dangers, the psychological dangers of being involved

08:43.480 --> 08:54.120
with it, then you end up with people like Benedict Howard, Ronald Reagan, and
Richard Nixon who do not have self-consciousness about the personal dangers, the

08:54.120 --> 09:04.760
moral dangers of chasing after power, whereas somebody like Barron, who is
certainly an imperfect person, as all people are, at least his saving grace, if

09:04.760 --> 09:15.940
he has one, is that he is well aware of the personal dangers of being involved
in a quest for power. When Spinrad tried to get the novel published in this

09:15.940 --> 09:24.120
country, he was unsuccessful, so he tried in Britain. But there was an outcry in
Parliament against the book. He relates the story for us. That novel had a lot

09:24.120 --> 09:32.940
of trouble. It was written under contract to Doubleday, who then rejected it.
You know, you have to remember the political climate of the era. They didn't

09:32.940 --> 09:42.220
reject it. They said, we'll publish it if you cut out all the sex, all the swear
words, and all the politics, which was, you know, the whole book. So it took a

09:42.220 --> 09:49.860
long time to resell that book here. In the meantime, I took it to Milford, to a
Milford conference, and Mike Moorcock was there, and he read it, and he liked

09:49.860 --> 09:59.120
it, and he serialized it in New World. So his first publication was actually in
England, in the magazine. Now, halfway through the serialization, I forget

09:59.120 --> 10:08.500
exactly which part, part three, part four, W.H. Smith, which was the biggest
distributor, still is the biggest distributor in England, refused to distribute

10:08.500 --> 10:17.920
the magazine because of the book. Now, at that time, New World had an Arts
Council grant, and the Arts Council was an organ of the British government. Now,

10:17.960 --> 10:27.340
the Arts Council supported the magazine against Smith publicly, and so the flap
in Parliament arose when certain right-wing members of Parliament were aghast

10:27.340 --> 10:38.460
that an organ of the British government, the Arts Council, was defending this
kind of stuff, and that's how it became a parliamentary issue. Bug Jack Barron is

10:38.460 --> 10:46.080
being made into a movie with a screenplay by Harlan Ellison and direction by
radical filmmaker Costa-Gavras. It should be interesting. More with Norman

10:46.080 --> 10:47.360
Spinrad next time.

