11:50.220 --> 11:54.240
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:10.380 --> 12:15.820
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:18.580 --> 12:20.260
And here are your hosts.

12:24.840 --> 12:32.480
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Norman Spinrad's 1979 science fiction novel,
A World Between, signaled a change in his fiction.

12:42.520 --> 12:46.680
A World Between is also a socially oriented novel, but there's a difference...

12:58.440 --> 13:13.280
...for an element in it. Spinrad explains. I would say in general that up until,
I guess, A World Between, really, a lot of my stuff was kind of critical

13:13.280 --> 13:24.200
fiction, critical of this, critical of existing societies, critical of various
things that were going on. A World Between is meant as a utopian novel, really,

13:24.340 --> 13:34.900
in any kind of way, and it's a prescriptive kind of book. It's more of
a...instead of presenting critical images of other things, the idea is to create

13:34.900 --> 13:45.640
a more positive image of a more positive kind of future. I think if you spend
enough time criticizing what exists, at some point you'll have some kind of

13:45.640 --> 13:53.040
moral obligation to present something more positive and replace what you find
negative.

13:57.780 --> 14:05.720
The setting for the novel is a fit one for a utopia. It takes place on the
planet Pacifica, a beautiful world of blue ocean and lush green islands that's

14:05.720 --> 14:13.340
been colonized by humans. Inhabitants of Pacifica live private lives in their
isolated islands. There are no large urban centers to cause pollution,

14:13.560 --> 14:21.140
overpopulation, or poverty. Even though they are physically isolated, the
Pacificans remain in close electronic contact with one another. They govern

14:21.140 --> 14:29.200
themselves, in fact, with a tight media web that allows them to vote immediately
on any issue of importance. But into this idyllic world comes two opposed

14:29.200 --> 14:38.000
political forces from Earth, bent on the ideological conquest of Pacifica. One
force is the Institute for Transcendental Science, a powerful organization whose

14:38.000 --> 14:49.940
goal is galactic unity under their control. They are extreme, and Spinrad says
they have two basic flaws. One is the unexamined, subtle male chauvinist bias of

14:49.940 --> 15:02.700
their culture. And the other one is the ultimate conviction that what they are
doing is the absolute most important thing in the universe, and that therefore

15:02.700 --> 15:19.180
they are morally entitled to run over other people's cultures and dishonors.
Absolutism, I guess, would be the kind of theocratic absolutism, would be their

15:19.180 --> 15:28.320
flaw. The other force is the Femocrats, a militant women's liberation group that
is also an extreme. The struggle of these two groups for control of planets all

15:28.320 --> 15:36.080
across the galaxy is called the Pink and Blue War. It's clearly a male-female
conflict, and so far every planet the two sides have approached has ended up on

15:36.080 --> 15:45.080
one side or the other. But Pacifica is different. Spinrad's utopia is a stable
and intelligent one. The Pacificans reject both extremes and even change the

15:45.080 --> 15:53.980
minds of a few of the combatants. We asked Spinrad about reactions to the book.
How did women, for instance, respond to the Femocratic women's livers? The

15:53.980 --> 16:08.080
strange thing about the reaction to that book has been that a certain number of
men have reacted in a kind of male-liberal guilt, male-feminist kind of reaction

16:08.080 --> 16:17.940
against that. For the most part, women have liked the book. Women have
identified with it more than men. And actually, I even got one or two good

16:17.940 --> 16:27.060
reviews in feminist places. I think that's not quite what I expected, but that
seems to be the way it happened. I have not gotten heavy feminist flack from

16:27.060 --> 16:37.280
that. A little bit, but not much. Not much, because I think women who are
involved in feminism, or have been, or know women who are, can recognize a

16:37.280 --> 16:47.040
certain aspect of the feminist movement in the Femocrats, whereas men who are
trying to show how liberated they are would not dream of admitting such a thing.

16:47.040 --> 16:52.440
A world between. A different sort of book for Norman Spinrad, and we'll have
more on him tomorrow.

16:59.860 --> 17:08.020
