18:14.920 --> 18:20.480
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

18:23.200 --> 18:24.980
And here are your hosts.

18:30.120 --> 18:39.340
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Norman Spinrad's most recent novel, Songs
from the Stars, was published by Simon & Schuster in 1980. The book describes a

18:39.340 --> 18:47.540
fragmented future society in a world devastated by nuclear war. This, of course,
is a typical Spinrad theme. But the novel also communicates the sense of wonder

18:47.540 --> 18:55.880
characteristic of good science fiction when it describes the marvels of contact
with an alien civilization. Society is split in two factions in Songs from the

18:55.880 --> 19:03.920
Stars. One faction is an Aquarian society which bans all technology, in fact,
anything having to do with science, since this was what was responsible for

19:03.920 --> 19:11.640
almost destroying the Earth. And the other faction are the black scientists who
keep technology alive and maintain an illicit smuggling operation with the

19:11.640 --> 19:21.600
Aquarian society. Spinrad talks about these opposed factions. It's a book
against duality. I mean, you have two fragmented societies. They're both...

19:24.560 --> 19:36.060
Both are kind of like half-societies. So the Aquarian society there is a very
nice thing that works, except it really only works because it accepts something

19:36.060 --> 19:51.300
from the black scientists, which it doesn't want to admit that it's accepted.
And the black scientists are, again, another kind of absolutism, which doesn't

19:51.300 --> 20:03.340
sell it. It's a kind of a... It's a book about higher unity, I guess. As usual
with Spinrad, the book's conflict reflects current social conditions. And then,

20:03.440 --> 20:11.460
you know, it mirrors the present thing in our society, where on the one hand you
have a great big space movement and people wanting to get into space and all the

20:11.460 --> 20:21.240
old people and all that stuff. On the other hand, you have a real atavistic neo
-Luddite movement, an anti-nuclear movement, which is really kind of willfully

20:21.240 --> 20:28.620
ignorant of a lot of things. In a way, these are the two things that could bring
about the crash.

20:32.080 --> 20:42.780
And as well as what would survive it. So I think it's basically a book about...
The grand philosophical attempt of that book is to try and bridge the gap

20:42.780 --> 20:55.600
between science and reason and, you know, feeling emotion and mysticism. And to,
you know, to point to a higher unity between the two things and away from the

20:55.600 --> 21:04.740
false dichotomies and false dualisms, which seem to be really destroying Western
civilization, that's a long statement. The protagonist in the book is a laid

21:04.740 --> 21:12.320
-back Aquarian, Clear Blue Lou. Along with his girl and a scientist, he travels
up to a satellite circling the Earth. There, the three of them receive

21:12.320 --> 21:20.420
communication from some incredibly advanced alien civilizations in another part
of the galaxy. With the knowledge sent by the helpful aliens, it seems the

21:20.420 --> 21:28.080
humans will solve their own problems, unite, and start progressing toward the
stars once more. We asked Spinrad that if and when we contact an alien

21:28.080 --> 21:39.320
civilization, is it likely they will be helpful rather than hostile? As I said
in the book, I do believe that any civilization that's going to last a million

21:39.320 --> 21:46.560
years, it's going to be a million years or whatever, or even a hundred thousand
years more advanced than us, that have been around that much longer, that much

21:46.560 --> 21:55.360
more advanced science, if it's going to survive for that length of its own
history, it's got to solve it, you know, it's got to be, by that time,

21:56.580 --> 22:06.020
philosophically and emotionally pretty together, or long since it destroyed
itself. I mean, we certainly will not survive a million years of our own history

22:06.020 --> 22:14.860
if it continues as it has, you know, in order that any civilization that
survives a million years of its own history has had to have gotten its

22:14.860 --> 22:29.160
political, psychological, and philosophical act together. And I don't see why,
you know, you know, and I do believe that if and when we run into that kind of

22:29.160 --> 22:39.040
really advanced civilizations, that they will, if not be directly actively
helpful, certainly will be benign and will not be interested in either eating us

22:39.040 --> 22:48.580
or conquering our planet or blowing us up or anything like that. Songs from the
Stars is a thoughtfully written book with a theme, but it's also good, exciting

22:48.580 --> 22:49.280
science fiction.

