24:21.280 --> 24:23.000
And here are your hosts.

24:27.540 --> 24:35.860
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. James P. Hogan's latest novel, Voyage from
Yesteryear, is a fascinating blend of computers, space exploration, and genetic

24:35.860 --> 24:42.760
engineering. It's about a robot probe that discovers a habitable planet ten
light years from Earth. But it's different than the usual probe imagined by

24:42.760 --> 24:51.820
science fiction authors. Right. This one is equipped to manufacture human
beings. Hogan explains. We read a lot of stories about starships that go on long

24:51.820 --> 25:01.740
voyages that take maybe centuries. And inevitably they've got frozen bodies or
bodies in suspended animation or something like that. But when you think about

25:01.740 --> 25:09.240
it, it seems rather an inefficient way to say, you know, if they're not doing
anything, the machines can fly the ship. The computers can get it there. The

25:09.240 --> 25:18.860
people aren't doing anything about it except, you know, just lying there
freezing. So, you know, why not let the machines fly the ship and make the

25:18.860 --> 25:29.660
people when you get there? If we look at the progress made in molecular biology
and genetic engineering in the last couple of decades, we already manufacture

25:29.660 --> 25:38.760
quite complex organic molecules to specifications, such as drugs and certain
anesthetics. If we just extrapolate that a little further, who's to say you

25:38.760 --> 25:47.640
couldn't make a complete set of human DNA? In other words, instead of sending
bodies and all the support equipment to freeze them and taking up all the space,

25:47.640 --> 25:52.380
why not just store

25:52.380 --> 26:05.740
all the genetic information necessary to make people electronically in the
computers and create them when you have found a planet that the instruments say

26:05.740 --> 26:14.240
they could survive on? So the computers make a race of humans, raise them, and
place them on the planet. It sounds a bit mechanical, a little inhuman perhaps,

26:14.580 --> 26:29.020
but Hogan thinks it could work out beautifully. So here's the interesting
possibility of a race that evolves from a first generation of embryos that were

26:29.020 --> 26:40.120
created and nurtured and raised by computers and robots, a machine-raised race.
And when you think about it, the relationship between the children and the

26:40.120 --> 26:50.440
machines does not really have to be a cold and sinister one at all. It could be
quite a charming and amusing one. The interesting thoughts that the book starts

26:50.440 --> 26:57.360
to play with is, here's a race of kids that are being raised by some

26:57.360 --> 27:09.840
very rational, direct, down-to-earth entities who don't double-talk or deceive
or have all these layers of human game-playing that we have to contend with. And

27:09.840 --> 27:15.860
they're being raised completely without

27:15.860 --> 27:28.440
any exposure to the conditioning of conditioned adults with their prejudices and
hatreds and taboos and a lot of the other nonsenses that make life so

27:28.440 --> 27:37.980
complicated in our society. As you might expect, these machine-raised humans are
eventually contacted by humans from Earth. Let's imagine that a mission from

27:37.980 --> 27:39.440
Earth eventually shows up.

27:42.460 --> 27:53.360
Virtually a big mission. This is a 20-year voyage, maybe. So we're talking about
a spaceship that maybe houses 20,000 people, virtually a space colony with

27:53.360 --> 28:04.660
engines, with its government, its military, its church organizations, its
commercial institutions. The whole of society in miniature with its time-proved

28:04.660 --> 28:18.960
mechanisms for controlling and subordinating a population, which traditionally a
ruling elite through history has imposed itself by restricting the flow of

28:18.960 --> 28:31.660
wealth and by offering protection either from real or imagined threats. So what
happens when a race of machine-raised people eventually collides with a race of

28:31.660 --> 28:39.940
people-raised people? And that's really what the story's all about. Voyage from
Yesteryear will be out in paperback at the end of July. Next week we'll have a

28:39.940 --> 28:41.820
series of shows on the works of James B. Hogan.

